docs.abstract: Rules and store technology can impede Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program recipients, but a pilot effort to expand access is picking up speed.
docs.snippet: Rules and store technology can impede Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program recipients, but a pilot effort to expand access is picking up speed.
docs.lead_paragraph: Whether they need more yeast for stress baking or the comfort of Kraft macaroni and cheese, Americans sequestered by social distancing are shopping for groceries online. But for many low-income households using food stamps, that can happen only in person.

headline.main: For Most Food Stamp Users, Online Shopping Isn’t an Option

docs.abstract: Tim Bray, an engineer who had been a vice president of Amazon’s cloud computing arm, said the firings were “evidence of a vein of toxicity running through the company culture.”
docs.snippet: Tim Bray, an engineer who had been a vice president of Amazon’s cloud computing arm, said the firings were “evidence of a vein of toxicity running through the company culture.”
docs.lead_paragraph: A prominent engineer and vice president of Amazon’s cloud computing arm said on Monday that he had quit “in dismay” over the recent firings of workers who had raised questions about workplace safety during the coronavirus pandemic.

headline.main: An Amazon Vice President Quit Over Firings of Employees Who Protested

docs.abstract: Google, Facebook, Amazon, Capital One and others are extending work-from-home policies to September and sometimes far beyond.
docs.snippet: Google, Facebook, Amazon, Capital One and others are extending work-from-home policies to September and sometimes far beyond.
docs.lead_paragraph: Even as President Trump has said “we have to get our country open again,” much of corporate America is in no rush to return employees to their campuses and skyscrapers. The companies are racing not to be the first back, but the last.

headline.main: White-Collar Companies Race to Be Last to Return to the Office

docs.abstract: The pandemic has intensified the push-pull between labor and the retail giant, which is required by European law to deal with unions — and has prospered anyway.
docs.snippet: The pandemic has intensified the push-pull between labor and the retail giant, which is required by European law to deal with unions — and has prospered anyway.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Workers at Amazon’s six mammoth French warehouses won some concessions from the company in late March: After hundreds of employees threatened to walk out unless the company better protected them from the coronavirus, the internet giant strengthened social distancing measures, provided masks and hand sanitizer and took employee temperatures.

headline.main: Amazon’s Showdown in France Tests Its Ability to Sidestep Labor
headline.print_headline: Amazon and a French Union Clash Over Safety, and Power

docs.abstract: The coalition, which includes Amazon, plans to pour $2 million into ads opposing President Trump’s call for higher package delivery rates and pressing for Congress to help the service.
docs.snippet: The coalition, which includes Amazon, plans to pour $2 million into ads opposing President Trump’s call for higher package delivery rates and pressing for Congress to help the service.
docs.lead_paragraph: A coalition of online retailers backed by Amazon began a seven-figure advertising blitz on Wednesday opposing President Trump’s demand that the beleaguered United States Postal Service ratchet up its package delivery rates to avoid bankruptcy amid the coronavirus crisis, its top lobbyist said.

headline.main: Online Retailers Spend Millions on Ads Backing Postal Service Bailout
